<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/TM-4690-1> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Deze arpillera toont een arrestatie: agenten van de geheime politie, herkenbaar aan hun donkere kleding en zwarte auto, arresteren een lokale man, of zelfs jongen. Dit was een gevaar voor veel mensen tijdens de dictatuur van Pinochet. De zon schijnt, zoals bijna altijd in arpilleras, waarmee de maakster wil aantonen dat het onderdeel uitmaakt van het dagelijkse leven. Het kan iedereen overkomen, en het leven gaat gewoon door. De bergen geven inzicht in waar het zich afspeelt, het toont hoe geografie ingezet wordt om te bepalen waar, en wie, we zijn.  \r\n\r\nArpilleras reflect a South American folk art that uses applique, embroidery and patchwork to depict scenes of everyday life. The Spanish word arpillera derives from an old Spanish word for burlap. They are sometimes called cuadros (squares). Most arpilleras are used as pictures and hung on walls. The most famous arpilleras and arpilleristas (the women who make them) are from Chile.\r\nArpilleras, or cuadros, depict daily-life events of the women and men (arpilleristas part of the Agrupación de los Familiares de los Detenidos Desaparecidos—AFDD) who have sewn them, and are largely aimed at denouncing the social injustices and violence experienced by the people of Chile during the Pinochet regime (1973-1990). As criticism of Pinochet increased, the government made it illegal to own or publically show arpilleras in the country.\r\nArpilleristas make their arpilleras with scrap material, they embroider and sew it on burlap. They are cheap to make and do not require high technical skills, thus people from all social backgrounds can make arpilleras. The cloths are mostly embroidered in a communal setting, sharing one's story with the others not only through the cloth, but also verbally by narrating one's experience.\r\n\r\nA Chilean mantanous landscape frames the background of this arpillera. There are five figures embroidered on  the cloth: tow women standing at opposite ends of the quadro; and two identical men between whom stand a blindfolded child. On the lower left side there is a car with the wirting \"detencion\" enbroidered on top. During the Pinochet regime a lot of political adversaries and many average people suspected of illegal or imporper activities were incartered and detained by the police. This arpillera might be representing the imprisonment of a young adult (what looks like a blindfolded child) by the police (the identically-rendered men)." .
